<h2>HVAC Systems in Georgia</h2>

<h3>Climate Considerations</h3>
<p>Georgia's humid subtropical climate creates unique challenges and opportunities for HVAC system design and operation. The state experiences hot, humid summers with average temperatures reaching 85-90¬∞F and humidity levels frequently exceeding 70%, creating substantial cooling loads that typically run from April through October. Winter heating requirements are relatively modest, with average low temperatures ranging from 35¬∞F in northern Georgia to 45¬∞F in southern coastal areas, meaning most homes require 3-4 times more cooling energy than heating energy annually.</p>

<p>The high humidity levels throughout Georgia make proper dehumidification a critical component of indoor comfort and air quality. HVAC systems must be properly sized and configured to remove moisture effectively while maintaining comfortable temperatures. Oversized systems that cycle on and off frequently often fail to adequately dehumidify, leading to comfort problems and potential indoor air quality issues. Variable-speed equipment and properly designed ductwork are particularly important in Georgia's climate to achieve optimal humidity control.</p>

<p>Georgia's long cooling season and high electricity rates during peak summer months make high-efficiency cooling systems particularly cost-effective. Heat pump systems are especially well-suited to Georgia's climate, providing efficient cooling during summer months and adequate heating during mild winter conditions. The state's minimal heating requirements mean that heat pumps can achieve excellent annual efficiency without the need for supplemental heating systems in most applications.</p>

